# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: columbus-ohio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research into this topic is fairly new, with few studies published before 2009, but has gained increasing attention in recent years.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A cross-sectoral, holistic approach is seen as an important feature of 100% renewable energy systems and is based on the assumption "that the best solutions can be found only if one focuses on the synergies between the sectors" of the energy system such as electricity, heat, transport or industry.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] No uniform definition for 100% renewable energy systems has been adopted across the published literature.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Recent studies show that a global transition to 100% renewable energy across all sectors – power, heat, transport and desalination well before 2050 is feasible.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Existing technologies, including storage, are capable of generating a secure energy supply at every hour throughout the year.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The sustainable energy system is more efficient and cost effective than the existing system.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) stated in their 2011 report that there is little that limits integrating renewable technologies for satisfying the total global energy demand.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Barriers to implementing the renewable energy plan are seen to be "primarily social and political, not technological or economic".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main obstacle against this scenario is the lack of political will.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] His conclusions have been disputed by other researchers.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson published a response that disputed the piece point by point and claimed that the authors were motivated by allegiance to energy technologies that the 2015 paper excluded.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies and he has rebutted their criticisms.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A followup paper was published by Jacobson and others in 2022, in which paths to 100% renewable energy by 2035 and 2050 were developed for 145 countries.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study concluded that a wind-water-solar (WWS) based system "requires less energy, costs less, and creates more jobs than business as usual".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The cost reduction was primarily due to the substantial (-56.4%) decrease in overall energy demand thanks to the increased efficiency of relying on renewable electricity for all energy needs.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2014, renewable sources such as wind, geothermal, solar, biomass, and burnt waste provided 19% of the total energy consumed worldwide, with roughly half of that coming from traditional use of biomass.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest sector in terms of energy consumption is electricity with a renewable share of 22.8%, most of it coming from hydropower with a share of 16.6%, followed by wind with 3.1%.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018, according to REN21, transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy .
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] At the national level, at least 30 nations already have renewable energy contributing more than 20% of the energy supply.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown more quickly than even advocates anticipated.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2019, however, it needs to grow six times faster to limit global warming to 2 °C (3.6 °F).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] 100% renewable energy in a country is typically a more challenging goal than carbon neutrality.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The latter is a climate mitigation target, politically decided by many countries, and may also be achieved by balancing the total carbon footprint of the country (not only emissions from energy and fuel) with carbon dioxide removal and carbon projects abroad.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018 according to REN21 transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow of Princeton University have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow us to maintain our quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low-carbon energy strategies are political rather than technological.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the 2013 *Post Carbon Pathways* report, which reviewed many international studies, the key roadblocks are: climate change denial, the fossil fuels lobby, political inaction, unsustainable energy consumption, outdated energy infrastructure, and financial constraints.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Studies have shown that Southeast Asia countries could achieve almost 100% renewable elecitricity based on solar, wind, and off-river pumped hydro energy storage at a competitive LCOE of around US$55–115/MWh.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Using 100% renewable energy was first suggested in a paper in *Science* published in 1975 by Danish physicist Bent Sørensen, which was followed by several other proposals.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1976, energy policy analyst Amory Lovins coined the term "soft energy path" to describe an alternative future where energy efficiency and appropriate renewable energy sources steadily replace a centralized energy system based on fossil and nuclear fuels.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1998, the first detailed analysis of scenarios with high shares of renewables were published.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] These were followed by the first detailed 100% scenarios.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2006, a PhD thesis was published by Czisch in which it was shown that in a 100% renewable scenario energy supply could match demand in every hour of the year in Europe and North Africa.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, Danish Energy professor Henrik Lund published a first paper in which he addresses the optimal combination of renewables, which was followed by several other papers on the transition to 100% renewable energy in Denmark.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Since then, Lund has been publishing several papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] After 2009, publications began to rise steeply, covering 100% scenarios for countries in Europe, America, Australia and other parts of the world.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Even in the early 21st century, it was extraordinary for scientists and decision-makers to consider the concept of 100% renewable electricity.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown much faster than even advocates had anticipated.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Wind turbines generate 39 percent of Danish electricity, and Denmark has many biogas digesters and waste-to-energy plants as well.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Together, wind and biomass provide 44% of the electricity consumed by the country's six million inhabitants.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2010, Portugal's 10 million people produced more than half their electricity from indigenous renewable energy resources.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Spain's 40 million inhabitants meet one-third of their electrical needs from renewables.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy has a history of strong public support.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In America, for example, a 2013 Gallup survey showed that two in three Americans want the U.S. to increase domestic energy production using solar power (76%), wind power (71%), and natural gas (65%).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Far fewer want more petroleum production (46%) and more nuclear power (37%).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Least favored is coal, with about one in three Americans favouring it.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supporters of 100% renewable energy do not consider nuclear power as renewable or sustainable due to perceived risks of disasters and high-level waste management, and consider carbon capture and storage to have limited safe storage potential.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] These constraints have also led to an interest in 100% renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A well established body of academic literature has been written over the past decade, evaluating scenarios for 100% renewable energy for various geographical areas.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In recent years, more detailed analyses have emerged from government and industry sources.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The incentive to use 100% renewable energy is created by global warming and ecological as well as economic concerns, post peak oil.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The first country to propose 100% renewable energy was Iceland, in 1998.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Proposals have been made for Japan in 2003, and for Australia in 2011.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania, Iceland, and Paraguay obtain essentially all of their electricity from renewable sources (Albania and Paraguay 100% from hydroelectricity, Iceland 72% hydro and 28% geothermal).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Norway obtains nearly all of its electricity from renewable sources (97 percent from hydropower).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Iceland proposed using hydrogen for transportation and its fishing fleet.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Australia proposed biofuel for those elements of transportation not easily converted to electricity.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The road map for the United States, commitment by Denmark, and Vision 2050 for Europe set a 2050 timeline for converting to 100% renewable energy, later reduced to 2040 in 2011.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Zero Carbon Britain 2030 proposes eliminating carbon emissions in Britain by 2030 by transitioning to renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2015, Hawaii enacted a law that the Renewable Portfolio Standard shall be 100 percent by 2045.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] This is often confused with renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] If electricity produced on the grid is 65 GWh from fossil fuel and 35 GWh from renewable energy and rooftop off grid solar produces 80 GWh of renewable energy, then the total renewable energy is 115 GWh and the total electricity on the grid is 100 GWh.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Cities like Paris and Strasbourg in France, planned to use 100% renewable energy by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] It is estimated that the world will spend an extra $8 trillion over the next 25 years to prolong the use of non-renewable resources, a cost that would be eliminated by transitioning instead to 100% renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research that has been published in Energy Policy suggests that converting the entire world to 100% renewable energy by 2050 is both possible and affordable, but requires political support.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] It would require building many more wind turbines and solar power systems but wouldn't utilize bioenergy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other changes involve use of electric cars and the development of enhanced transmission grids and storage.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] As part of the Paris Agreement, countries periodically update their climate change targets for the future, by 2018 no G20 country had committed to a 100% renewable target.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Until 2018, there were 181 peer-reviewed papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, 100% renewable energy was also mentioned in the Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5 °C as a potential means to "expand the range of 1.5 °C pathways", if the findings can be corroborated.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2021, wind and solar were consistently increasing their share worldwide, but still represented just 5% of global primary energy consumption, albeit far more of useful energy consumption.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Morgan Asset Management (the biggest lender to fossil fuels in the world) analyzed renewable energy forecasts made by eight scientists and research bodies (including Bent Sorensen, Mark Z.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, Amory Lovins) between 1970 and 2020 and claimed that all of them were unrealistically optimistic as they ignored "energy density, intermittency and the complex realities of incumbent energy systems".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some other places have high percentages, for example the electricity sector in Denmark, as of 2014, is 45% wind power, with plans in place to reach 85%.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The electricity sector in Canada and the electricity sector in New Zealand have even higher percentages of renewables (mostly hydro), 65% and 75% respectively, and Austria is approaching 70%.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2015, the electricity sector in Germany sometimes meets almost 100% of the electricity demand with PV and wind power, and renewable electricity is over 25%.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania has 94.8% of installed capacity as hydroelectric, 5.2% diesel generator; but Albania imports 39% of its electricity.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2016, Portugal achieved 100% renewable electricity for four days between 7 and 11 May, partly because efficient energy use had reduced electricity demand.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] France and Sweden have low carbon intensity, since they predominantly use a mixture of nuclear power and hydroelectricity.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018 Scotland met 76% of their demand from renewable sources.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Although electricity is currently around a quarter of world energy supply and consumption; primary energy use is expected to decrease with renewable energy deployment as electricity use increases, as it is likely to be combined with some degree of further electrification.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, electric cars achieve much better fuel efficiency than fossil fuel cars, and another example is renewable heat such as in the case of Denmark, which is proposing to move to greater use of heat pumps for heating buildings to provide multiple kilowatts of heat per kilowatt of electricity.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other electricity generating sources are considered clean, though not necessarily renewable, as they also do not emit carbon dioxide or other greenhouse gases and air pollutants.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest of these is nuclear energy, which produces no emissions.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some argue that transitioning to 100% renewable energy would be too slow to limit climate change, and that closing down nuclear power stations is a mistake.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Carbon capture and storage projects may still use coal or natural gas but capture carbon dioxide for storage or alternative uses.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Pathways to eliminate greenhouse gases may include these in addition to renewable energy to save money, or to avoid shutting down existing plants and allow for flexibility in designing a carbon-free electric grid.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018, California passed SB 100, which mandates 100% clean, carbon-free by 2045, including a 60% renewable electricity goal by 2030.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] 2019 legislation in Washington also requires 100% clean electricity by 2045, eliminating coal by 2025.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Further states and territories to require 100% carbon-free electricity are Hawaii, Maine, Minnesota, Nevada, New Mexico, New York, Virginia, Puerto Rico, and Washington, DC.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to a study by Global Energy Monitor, China is expected to generate 1,200 gigawatts of renewable energy (wind and solar) by 2025.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, the most significant barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low carbon energy strategies, at the pace required to prevent runaway climate change, are primarily political and not technological.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] IPCC scenarios "generally indicate that growth in renewable energy will be widespread around the world".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The IPCC said that if governments were supportive, and the full complement of renewable energy technologies were deployed, renewable energy supply could account for almost 80% of the world's energy use within forty years.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Rajendra Pachauri, chairman of the IPCC, said the necessary investment in renewables would cost only about 1% of global GDP annually.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] This approach could contain greenhouse gas levels to less than 450 parts per million, the safe level beyond which climate change becomes catastrophic and irreversible.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow societies to maintain their quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown founder and president of the Earth Policy Institute, a nonprofit research organization based in Washington, D.C., says a rapid transition to 100% renewable energy is both possible and necessary.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown compares with the U.S. entry into World War II and the subsequent rapid mobilization and transformation of the US industry and economy.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A quick transition to 100% renewable energy and saving of our civilization is proposed by Brown to follow an approach with similar urgency.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to World Bank the "below 2°C" climate scenario requires 3 billions of tonnes of metals and minerals by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supply of mined resources such as zinc, molybdenum, silver, nickel, copper must increase by up to 500%.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A 2018 study analysed the metal requirements to transition the global energy system up to 2060.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Currently used battery technologies and known reserves are not compatible with the transition scenario as a result of insufficient cobalt and lithium reserves.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Batteries containing less or no cobalt are feasible.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Lithium is much more difficult to replace with maintained performance and cost.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review suggests large institutions are prone to resisting "the challenge of 100% RE scenarios based on the dogma that the world cannot do without fossil fuels and nuclear energy".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Institutions that have received extensive criticism include the International Energy Agency and the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, with the latter also being criticized for not including studies on 100% RE systems in their IPCC reports.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A report found that China is about to produce "almost 95% of the world's polysilicon and the ingots and wafers" of the solar panel supply chain, with this level of concentration in any global supply chain "would represent a considerable vulnerability".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] One of the main obstacles to 100% renewable energy is the intermittency or variability of renewable energy sources – such as times when sufficient amounts of energy can be generated neither via wind nor via solar power ("Dunkelflauten").
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to Amory Lovins the electricity grid alone can compensate for variability, just as it routinely backs up nonworking coal-fired and nuclear plants with working ones.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, it may cost 40% more to reduce carbon emissions without carbon dioxide capture.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study introduced the term "firm low-carbon energy source" (e.g. nuclear, geothermal), which is intended to operate along "fast-burst" sources (e.g. batteries) and "fuel saving" (VRE).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] The International Energy Agency says that there has been too much attention on issue of the variability of renewable electricity production.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Variability is rarely a barrier to increased renewable energy deployment when dispatchable generation such as hydroelectricity or solar thermal storage is also available.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] But at high levels of market penetration it requires careful analysis and management, and additional costs may be required for back-up or system modification.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Hydropower is currently the only large scale low-carbon seasonal energy storage.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In countries with high variation in energy demand by season (for example the UK uses far more gas for heating in the winter than it uses electricity) but lacking hydropower electrical interconnectors to countries with lots of hydropower (e.g.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] UK - Norway), electricity from hydropower is likely to be insufficient and development of a hydrogen economy would likely be needed: this is being trialled in the UK and 8 TWh of inter-seasonal hydrogen energy storage has been proposed.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] In Australia, as well as storing renewable energy as hydrogen, it is also proposed to be exported in the form of ammonia.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] McKinsey estimates that it will cost 7.5% of global domestic product between 2021 and 2050 to achieve net zero (not 100% renewable, which will be more expensive).
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Current spending is just over half of this.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review identified major gaps and neglected aspects – open research questions – in the 100% RE literature.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] Full decaronization of the energy system by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p01] 7.16 for renewable target and 12 for national target.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has said that there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a 2011 review of 164 recent scenarios of future renewable energy growth, the report noted that the majority expected renewable sources to supply more than 17% of total energy by 2030, and 27% by 2050; the highest forecast projected 43% supplied by renewables by 2030 and 77% by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2011, the refereed journal *Energy Policy* published two articles by Mark Z.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson, a professor of engineering at Stanford University, and research scientist Mark A.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Delucchi, about changing the energy supply mix and "Providing all global energy with wind, water, and solar power".
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The articles analyze the feasibility of providing worldwide energy for electric power, transportation, and heating/cooling from wind, water, and sunlight (WWS), which are safe clean options.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part I, Jacobson and Delucchi discuss WWS energy system characteristics, aspects of energy demand, WWS resource availability, WWS devices needed, and material requirements.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] They estimate that 3,800,000 5 MW wind turbines, 5350 100 MW geothermal power plants, and 270 new 1300 MW hydroelectric power plants would be required.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In terms of solar power, an additional 49,000 300 MW concentrating solar plants, 40,000 300 MW solar photovoltaic power plants, and 1.7 billion 3 kW rooftop photovoltaic systems would also be needed.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Such an extensive WWS infrastructure could decrease world power demand by 30%.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part II, Jacobson and Delucchi address variability of supply, system economics, and energy policy initiatives associated with a WWS system.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The authors advocate producing all new energy with WWS by 2030 and replacing existing energy supply arrangements by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Energy costs with a WWS system should be similar to today's energy costs.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In general, Jacobson has said wind, water and solar technologies can provide 100 percent of the world's energy, eliminating all fossil fuels.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] 0.1% of the time would require generation from other sources.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In March 2012, Denmark's parliament agreed on a comprehensive new set of promotional programs for energy efficiency and renewable energy aimed at reaching 100 percent of electricity, heat and fuels from renewables by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] IRENEC is an annual conference on 100% renewable energy started in 2011 by Eurosolar Turkey.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] More recently, Jacobson and his colleagues have developed detailed proposals for switching to 100% renewable energy produced by wind, water and sunlight, for New York, California and Washington states, by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] As of 2014, a more expansive new plan for the 50 states has been drawn up, which includes an online interactive map showing the renewable resource potential of each of the 50 states.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The 50-state plan is part of The Solutions Project, an independent outreach effort led by Jacobson, actor Mark Ruffalo, and film director Josh Fox.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Debate over detailed plans remain, but transformations in global energy services based entirely around renewable energy are in principle technically practicable, economically feasible, socially viable, and so realisable.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] This prospect underpins the ambitious commitment by Germany, one of the world's most successful industrial economies, to undertake a major energy transition, Energiewende.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015 a study was published in *Energy and Environmental Science* that describes a pathway to 100% renewable energy in the United States by 2050 without using biomass.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Implementation of this roadmap is regarded as both environmentally and economically feasible and reasonable, as by 2050 it would save about $600 billion of health costs a year due to reduced air pollution and $3.3 trillion global warming costs.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] This would translate in yearly cost savings per head of around $8300 compared to a business as usual pathway.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to that study, barriers that could hamper implementation are neither technical nor economic but social and political, as most people didn't know that benefits from such a transformation far exceeded the costs.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In June 2017, twenty-one researchers published an article in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America* rejecting Jacobson's earlier *PNAS* article, accusing him of modeling errors and of using invalid modeling tools.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] They further asserted he made implausible assumptions through his reliance upon increasing national energy storage from 43 minutes to 7 weeks, increasing hydrogen production by 100,000%, and increasing hydropower by the equivalent of 600 Hoover Dams.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Victor called Jacobson's work "dangerous" and Ken Caldeira emphasized that increasing hydropower output by 1,300 gigawatts, a 25% increase, is the equivalent flow of 100 Mississippi Rivers.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson published a response in the same issue of the *PNAS* and also authored a blog post where he asserted the researchers were advocates of the fossil fuel industry.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Another study published in 2017 confirmed the earlier results for a 100% renewable power system for North America, without changes in hydropower assumptions, but with more realistic emphasis on a balanced storage portfolio, in particular seasonal storage, and for competitive economics.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015, Jacobson and Delucchi, together with Mary Cameron and Bethany Frew, examined with computer simulation (Loadmatch), in more detail how a wind-water-solar (WWS) system can track the energy demand from minute to minute.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] This turned out to be possible in the United States for 6 years, including WWS variability by extreme weather events.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2017, the plan was further developed for 139 countries by a team of 27 researchers and in 2018, Jacobson and Delucchi with Mary Cameron and Brian Mathiesen published the Loadmatch results for 20 regions in which the 139 countries in the world are divided.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to this research, a WWS system can follow the demand in all regions.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The program has been carried out for each region 10-20 times with adapted input for the storage capacities, until a solution was found in which the energy demand was followed, per half minute for 5 years, with low costs.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2020, Jacobson clarified in a textbook computer simulation results of a WWS energy system.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] To match demand with supply every minute more solar and wind farms and high-voltage lines must be installed than to match year-averaged demand and supply.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] Oversizing (also in a conventional energy system) ensures that the demand can be followed during peak hours, but causes unused supply during off-peak hours.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a WWS system, more energy exchange between areas leads to more transmission loss.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The table shows WWS supply, unused supply, losses and end-use, in GW average power to reliably supply the world and four major regions with energy by 2050.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] See textbook Table 8.10; energy in TWh is divided by 26.3 kh (1000 hours) to get power in GW.
[src:columbus-ohio/100-renewable-energy-p02] The bottom row is the storage capacity of pumped hydro plants (Table 8.7).
[src:columbus-ohio/16-east-broad-street] From 1927 to 1939, the eleventh floor of the building served as the office for the National Football League.
[src:columbus-ohio/16-east-broad-street] Carr, a Columbus native, was president of the NFL at the time.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] The magazine published its first issue as *UWeekly* on September 21, 2005.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] At the time, it was met with a chilly reception from Ohio State's official daily student newspaper, The Lantern, where faculty adviser Sonya Humes instituted a policy banning any members of The Lantern from writing for *UWeekly*.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] Despite this initial hostility, both publications continue to co-exist relatively peacefully on the Ohio State campus.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] In 2014, *UWeekly* became the country's only weekly college publication to publish in a glossy, magazine format.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] In January 2016, the magazine was renamed to *1870 Magazine*.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] The January 2016 issue was labeled the "Inaugural Issue"; however, the magazine's website, *1870 Now*, remains at uweekly.com.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] The sections of *UWeekly* include Campus News, Ohio State Sports, The Hookup (Entertainment) and Music and are included in the paper weekly.
[src:columbus-ohio/1870-magazine] Each edition of the paper also includes an Opinion page, Instagram photos #asseenoncampus, an event calendar and a Fashion column.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The **1910 streetcar strike** was a union protest against labor practices by the Columbus Railway and Light Co. in Columbus, Ohio in 1910.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The summertime strike began as peaceful protests, but led to thousands rioting throughout the city, injuring hundreds of people.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] Conditions for the streetcar workers were difficult at the time.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The operators worked for only 19–20 cents per hour, worked 60–65 hours per week, and worked for years without a day off.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] These conditions led to a high turnover rate, yet the job was not complicated and workers could be easily replaced, prompting the adverse working conditions.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The Columbus Railway and Light Co. paid its riders to report on irregular employee activities, and the company would not require hearings before firing employees for dishonesty.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] In early 1910, 35 employees of the company met with manager E.K.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The company fired the entire group as a result.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] In March, about half of the Columbus Railway and Light Company's employees formed a local chapter of the Amalgamated Association of Street and Electric Railway Employees labor union.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The union sought the reinstatement of the 35 workers, along with pay raises, better working conditions, and job stability.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The streetcar company chose a hard-line position, with no compromise offered.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The public primarily sided with the union.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The Columbus Chamber of Commerce, anticipating conflict, hosted a mandatory meeting between the union and company in June 1910.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] On July 23, its hearings concluded, finding that both parties were partly at fault, and that a peaceful resolution should be found.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The meeting mostly added to tensions, however, and the strike began the next day at 4 am.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The union's chapter had grown to 600 members by this point.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] They planned to not show up for work, instead selling union buttons around the city and picketing the company's streetcar barns.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The streetcar company chose to hire strikebreakers at $30 per week, over double the standard wage of $12.50.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] They also hired a special policing force, supplied by the local John J.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] Mahoney Detective Agency, to protect the streetcars and facilities.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The strike ended up more serious, as crowds barricaded streetcar tracks and threw bricks and rocks into the streetcars.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The company police responded with gunfire.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] That night, 76 people were arrested, though riots continued on the following day.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] Mayor George Sidney Marshall called in about 5,000 members of the Ohio National Guard.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] The troops kept order in the city until their departure on August 7.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] More rioting than took place, with shootings, barricades, stonings, and empty streetcars blown up with dynamite.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] It led to the National Guard returning, and the union and public more so aiming for a peaceful end to the riots.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] Still, about 3,000 to 4,000 strikers, sympathizers, and disrupters continued to riot.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] It led to a bad public image of the city, hurting business activity, and worrying the city planning for a state fair in September.
[src:columbus-ohio/1910-columbus-streetcar-strike] On October 18, the union admitted defeat, and its 570 striking workers either returned to work or moved to work elsewhere in Columbus, or for Cleveland streetcar companies.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The **1994 North American cold wave** occurred over the midwestern and eastern regions of the United States and southern Canada in January 1994.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The cold wave caused over 100 deaths in the United States.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Two notable cold air events took place from January 18–19 and January 21–22.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] There were 67 minimum temperature records set on January 19.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] During this time, much of the United States experienced its coldest temperatures since a major storm on February 20, 1934.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Cold air outbreaks are characterized by strong upper-level troughs in the atmosphere, with ridges usually located up and downstream.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] On January 17, 1994, the 500 millibar (mb) height contours showed the low-pressure center was situated near the border of Ontario and Manitoba, just north of Minnesota, with the trough axis stretching down into the Upper Midwest.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The 500 mb height contours on January 18 showed the strong trough over the Great Lakes region extending southward that brought cold air down from the North Pole.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] MERRA-2 reanalysis detailed the cold air funneling into the Upper Midwest from Canada on January 18, with strong winds out of the northwest.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The surface analysis map on January 18 showed a low-level ridge over the Upper Midwest and surface winds blowing out of the northwest.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The surface anticyclones on January 18 and 21 both exceeded 1,040 mbar (104 kPa) and moved to the southeast, bringing cold air to much of the eastern half of the United States.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] By January 19, the upper levels showed a retreat of the low-pressure center, however, shortwave troughs were still located near the United States, and surface temperature effects with the strong anticyclone were felt for days to come.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Snow was associated with this cold weather in many regions.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] From January 17–18, a snowstorm affected areas from the Ozarks to New England.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Ice affected most of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Accumulations of sleet and freezing rain in New York City were in excess of an inch.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] January 1994 was a month of extremes in Canada.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Temperatures in the Yukon approached −50 °C (−58 °F).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] In Yellowknife, Northwest Territories, the temperature did not exceed −40 °C (−40 °F) for many days.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] In Windsor, Ontario, the coldest temperature since 1885 was recorded on January 19 at −29 °C (−20 °F).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] On January 16, Scarborough, Ontario, recorded an all-time record low temperature of −35.2 °C (−31.4 °F), several degrees colder than the official coldest record for Toronto, which now includes Scarborough.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Toronto recorded its coldest January on record with −12.4 °C (9.7 °F) at the airport.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The cold air was also accompanied by large snowfalls.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The western side of Lake Ontario saw 50 centimeters (20 inches).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Rapid melting and freezing near the end of January caused Toronto Pearson International Airport to close for the first time in 60 years.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Water shortages were also common in Goose Bay, Labrador, due to extreme temperatures.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] On January 16, the Watertown, New York, International Airport set an all-time record low of −43 °F (−42 °C), while Watertown observed its coldest January on record, with a mean temperature of 5.39 °F (−14.78 °C).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The Syracuse, New York, Hancock International Airport recorded a monthly mean temperature of 12.6 °F (−10.8 °C), a record low for January.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The lowest temperature seen in Sussex County, New Jersey, was −26 °F (−32.2 °C) on January 21, 1994.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Washington National Airport (later renamed Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport) had a new record-low maximum temperature for the 20th century of 8 °F (−13.3 °C).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Maine had its coldest month since February 1934 and its coldest January since 1920.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] It was Maine's coldest winter since 1970–71, New Hampshire's since 1976–77, and Vermont's since 1958–59.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Erie, Pennsylvania, hit −18 °F (−27.8 °C), a record at that time.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Pittsburgh saw its record-low temperature of −22 °F (−30 °C) on January 19.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Indiana set state records on January 19.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] On January 19, the temperature in New Whiteland, Indiana, dropped to −36 °F (−37.8 °C), the record-lowest temperature in the state.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] In Indianapolis, temperatures plunged to a new record low of −27 °F (−32.8 °C), refreshing the record low set in December 1989 at −23 °F (−30.6 °C) and the January record low of −22 °F (−30.0 °C) set in 1985.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Cincinnati, Ohio, reached a temperature of −24 °F (−31.1 °C), just one degree short of the record low.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Columbus saw a record −22 °F (−30.0 °C), and Cleveland reached a record of −20 °F (−28.9 °C).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Akron set a record-low temperature at −25 °F (−32 °C).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Minneapolis–Saint Paul was one of the areas that felt major impacts from the cold wave.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] For 142 continuous hours during January 13–19, the temperature recorded at Minneapolis–Saint Paul International Airport stayed at or below zero.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] This was the sixth-longest stretch on record from 1873 to 2014.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Governor Arne Carlson closed all public schools in Minnesota on January 18, with wind chills of −48 °F (−44 °C) and morning air temperatures of −26 °F (−32 °C).
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] On January 6–7, 1994, Lake County, Minnesota, set records for the largest snow in one day as well as the most snow in one storm.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Chicago, Illinois, reached −21 °F (−29.4 °C) with wind chills of around −55 °F (−48.3 °C), with suburbs in the then 9 Million Metro Area reaching nearly -30.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The coldest day of the 1990s in Chicago by far.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Almost all primary and secondary schools in Chicago were closed that day.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Richard Daley, then mayor of Chicago advised residents not to go outside if they don't have to.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Nearly all schools in the area were closed and four people in Cook County, Illinois, died from hypothermia.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Hundreds of drivers per hour complained to the AAA-Chicago Motor Club about dead automobile batteries, fuel injectors being too cold and other vehicle issues and United Airlines canceled almost half of its flights.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Multiple complaints were raised about lack of power due to severed electricity lines and water companies stopped water supply to homes due to pipe explosions.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Many apartment renters complained to Cook County about insufficient heat.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Kentucky set state records on January 19.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The minimum record temperature in Kentucky was −37 °F (−38.3 °C) in Shelbyville on that day.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] A single-storm snowfall record was set in Louisville, Kentucky, with 16 inches (410 mm) of snow recorded.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The meteorological event was dramatized in the 2024 film *Ordinary Angels*.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] Directed by Jon Gunn and starring Hilary Swank, the film tells the true story of Louisville residents teaming up to shovel a path for Ed Schmitt (Alan Ritchson) so that he could drive his ill daughter, Michelle, to the hospital for a liver transplant.
[src:columbus-ohio/1994-north-american-cold-wave] The film premiered on February 23, 2024, 30 years and 1 month after the dissipation of the actual cold wave.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The **2004 United States presidential election in Ohio** took place on November 2, 2004, and was part of the 2004 United States presidential election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Voters chose 20 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Ohio was won by incumbent President George W.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Prior to the election, most news organizations considered Ohio as a swing state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The state's economic situation gave hope for John Kerry.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In the end, the state became the deciding factor of the entire election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Kerry conceded the state, and the entire election, the morning following election night, as Bush won the state and its 20 electoral votes.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The close contest was the subject of the 2006 documentary film *...So Goes the Nation*, the title of which is a reference to Ohio's 2004 status as a crucial swing state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] As of the 2024 U.S. presidential election, this is the last time Ohio voted more Democratic than the nation as a whole, as well as the last time where Hamilton County, the home of Cincinnati, voted for a Republican presidential candidate.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Bush became the first Republican to win the White House without carrying Stark County since Benjamin Harrison in 1888.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] There were 12 news organizations that made state-by-state predictions of the election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Here are their last predictions before election day.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Pre-election polling showed a lot of volatility throughout the general election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In September, Bush was gaining momentum here, reaching over 50% in several polls and even reaching double digit margins in some.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] By October, Kerry gained back momentum as he started winning many of the polls, leading with from 48% to as high as 50%.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The last 3 polls averaged Kerry leading 49% to 48%.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Bush visited the state 18 times to Kerry's 23 times.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Almost every week, over $10 million was spent on television advertising.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] CNN's exit polling showed that Bush barely won the state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] He won with 52% among male voters, while it was tied 50–50 among female voters.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] 53% of the voters approved of Bush's job as president.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Bush dominated in the rural areas, while Kerry dominated and won most of the counties with large populations.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Overall, Bush won most of the counties and congressional districts in the state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] All the congressional districts Kerry won were in the northern section of the state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Bush won 13 of 18 congressional districts, including one held by a Democrat.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Technically the voters of Ohio cast their ballots for electors: representatives to the Electoral College.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Ohio is allocated 20 electors because it has 18 congressional districts and 2 senators.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] All candidates who appear on the ballot or qualify to receive write-in votes must submit a list of 20 electors, who pledge to vote for their candidate and his or her running mate.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Whoever wins the majority of votes in the state is awarded all 20 electoral votes.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Their chosen electors then vote for president and vice president.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Although electors are pledged to their candidate and running mate, they are not obligated to vote for them.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] An elector who votes for someone other than his or her candidate is known as a faithless elector.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The electors of each state and the District of Columbia met on December 13, 2004, to cast their votes for president and vice president.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Electoral College itself never meets as one body.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Instead the electors from each state and the District of Columbia met in their respective capitols.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The following were the members of the Electoral College from the state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Ohio's polling locations and equipment are determined by two Democrats and two Republicans serving on the county's Board of Elections, which ensures that any decision made about polling resources is bipartisan.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Senate voted the objection down 74–1; the House voted the objection down 267–31.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] At the time, it was only the second congressional objection to an entire U.S. state's electoral delegation in American history; the first instance was in 1877, when all the electors from three Southern states in the 1876 United States presidential election were challenged, and one from Oregon.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The third instance was in 2021, when Republicans objected to the certification of the electors from Arizona and Pennsylvania.
[src:columbus-ohio/2004-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] An objection to a single faithless elector was also filed in 1969.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The **2008 United States presidential election in Ohio** took place on November 4, 2008, which was part of the 2008 United States presidential election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Ohio was won by Democratic nominee Barack Obama with a 4.59% margin of victory.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Prior to the election, most news organizations considered this state as a major swing state and bellwether.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Both major party candidates visited Ohio extensively and campaigned throughout the state, trying to sway moderates and independent voters to their side.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The polls in Ohio were fairly even throughout the campaign but Obama had a slight lead as Election Day drew closer.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In the end, Obama flipped Ohio into the Democratic column.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Obama's 2,940,044 votes are the most received by a Democratic presidential candidate in the state's history.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Despite this fact, Obama became the first Democrat ever to win the White House without carrying Pike County.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] On the other hand, Obama became the first Democrat to win Hamilton County since 1964.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] As of the 2024 presidential election, this is the last election in which Lake County, Monroe County, Belmont County, Tuscarawas County, and Jefferson County voted for a Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Ohio is also one of only three states that backed Obama twice that would go on to vote against his vice president Joe Biden in 2020, the other two being Florida and Iowa.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] There were 16 news organizations who made state-by-state predictions of the election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] During most of the summer and September, McCain led many state polls, many by 50% or more.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Rasmussen had McCain leading with as high as 51% in September.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] But many voters in the state changed their minds as Obama later gained a steady lead in most polls taken starting in the beginning of October (around the time of the 2008 financial crisis).
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In a major swing state, Obama spent over $28 million to McCain's $24 million.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Republican ticket visited the state 28 times, compared to the Obama ticket's 22 times.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Going into the election, both McCain and Obama knew that Ohio was a crucial state.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Earlier in the primary season, Ohio had given a major comeback victory to Hillary Clinton.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Both candidates campaigned heavily throughout the state in hopes of winning its 20 electoral votes.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] As no Republican has ever won the presidency without winning Ohio, it was seen in particular as a "must-win" state for McCain.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Bush's narrow wins in 2000 (by 3.51% against Al Gore) and 2004 (2.10% against John Kerry) proved critical in Bush's narrow wins nationally.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Obama won Ohio's 20 electoral votes by a margin of 4.59%.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] McCain did best in the Republican base in the center and western regions, composed of relatively rural areas combined with Cincinnati and Columbus' heavily Republican suburbs.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In addition, McCain won all but four counties in the Appalachian southeast, mirroring the troubles Obama had throughout this region.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] On the other hand, Obama did best in the Democratic base—Cleveland (where he won almost 70% of the vote), Youngstown and the heavily unionized counties next to Pennsylvania.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] However, he was unable to significantly improve upon John Kerry's performance in these areas.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] More surprisingly, the cities of Cincinnati and Columbus gave Obama strong support.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Cincinnati, the only major city that didn't vote for Franklin D.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Roosevelt, voted Democratic for the first time since 1964.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Columbus, a city shifting to the Democrats, also voted for Obama by a three-to-two margin.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In addition, Obama won several northern counties along the shore of Lake Erie that John Kerry had lost in 2004.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] As polls closed and results were coming in on Election Night, Republican strategist and adviser Karl Rove joined Brit Hume on Fox News offering analysis.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Rove was discussing the impact an Ohio loss would have on McCain's chances of winning the election.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] "If he loses Ohio," Rove stated of McCain, "he goes from 286, which the Republicans carried in 2004, down to 266, and that puts him below the 270 threshold needed to win the White House.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] So he'd not only need to sweep the rest of these states which were won by the Republicans in 2004, he'd also need to pick up something as well." In an untimely moment, Hume broke in.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Although Barack Obama won the state, John McCain carried ten of the state's 18 congressional districts, including three districts that simultaneously elected a Democrat.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Obama carried eight districts, including one district held by a Republican.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Technically, the voters of Ohio cast their ballots for electors: representatives to the Electoral College.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] All candidates who appear on the ballot or qualify to receive write-in votes must submit a list of 20 electors, who pledge to vote for their candidate and their running mate.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] An elector who votes for someone other than their candidate is known as a faithless elector.
[src:columbus-ohio/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The electors of each state and the District of Columbia met on December 15, 2008, to cast their votes for president and vice president.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus originated as several Native American settlements along the Scioto River.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The first European settlement was Franklinton, now a city neighborhood, in 1797.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus was founded in 1812 at the confluence of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers and was named after Italian explorer Christopher Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It was planned as the state capital due to its central location and officially became the capital in 1816.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city grew steadily through the 19th century as a transportation and industrial hub via the National Road, Ohio and Erie Canal, and several railroads.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Starting in the 1950s, Columbus experienced rapid suburban growth, becoming Ohio's largest city by area and population by the early 1990s.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus diversified economically in the late 20th and early 21st centuries as a center for finance, insurance, education, and technology.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 2020s, the city became a major center for high technology, innovation, and advanced manufacturing, particularly in the fields of artificial intelligence, robotics, and semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Greater Columbus area is further home to the headquarters of *Fortune* 500 companies Cardinal Health, Nationwide, American Electric Power, Huntington Bancshares and Vertiv.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It hosts cultural institutions such as the Columbus Museum of Art, COSI, Franklin Park Conservatory and Ohio Theatre.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's major league professional sports teams include the Columbus Blue Jackets (NHL) and Columbus Crew (MLS).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city of Columbus was named after 15th-century Italian explorer Christopher Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It may be the largest city in the world named for the explorer (as the name of the Sri Lankan city of Colombo is of Sinhala origin), who sailed to and settled parts of the Americas on behalf of Isabella I of Castile and Spain.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Since the late 20th century, historians have criticized Columbus for initiating the European conquest of America and for abuse, enslavement, and subjugation of natives.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Efforts to remove symbols related to the explorer in the city date to the 1990s.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Amid the George Floyd protests in 2020, several petitions pushed for the city to be renamed.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2021, the iconic 22-foot tall statue of Christopher Columbus was removed from the south side of City Hall.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Nicknames for the city have included "the Discovery City", "Arch City", "Cap City", "Cowtown", "The Biggest Small Town in America" and "Cbus".
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Between 1000 B.C. and 1700 A.D., the Columbus metropolitan area was a center to indigenous cultures known as the Mound Builders, including the Adena, Hopewell and Fort Ancient peoples.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Remaining physical evidence of the cultures are their burial mounds and what they contained.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Most of Central Ohio's remaining mounds are located outside of Columbus city boundaries, though the Shrum Mound is maintained, now as part of a public park and historic site.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's Mound Street derives its name from a mound that existed by the intersection of Mound and High Streets.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The mound's clay was used in bricks for most of the city's initial brick buildings; many were subsequently used in the Ohio Statehouse.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's Ohio History Center maintains a collection of artifacts from these cultures.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The area including present-day Columbus once comprised the Ohio Country, under the nominal control of the French colonial empire through the Viceroyalty of New France from 1663 until 1763.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 18th century, European traders flocked to the area, attracted by the fur trade.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The area was often caught between warring factions, including American Indian and European interests.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 1740s, Pennsylvania traders overran the territory until the French forcibly evicted them.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Fighting for control of the territory in the French and Indian War became part of the Seven Years' War.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Up until the American Revolution, Central Ohio had continuously been the home of numerous indigenous villages.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] A Mingo village was located at the forks of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers, with Shawnee villages to the south and Wyandot and Delaware villages to the north.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Colonial militiamen burned down the Mingo village in 1774 during a raid.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] After the American Revolution, the Virginia Military District became part of the Ohio Country as a territory of Virginia.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Colonists from the East Coast moved in, but rather than finding an empty frontier, they encountered people of the Miami, Delaware, Wyandot, Shawnee and Mingo nations, as well as European traders.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The tribes resisted expansion by the fledgling United States, leading to years of bitter conflict.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The decisive Battle of Fallen Timbers resulted in the Treaty of Greenville in 1795, which finally opened the way for new settlements.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] By 1797, a young surveyor from Virginia named Lucas Sullivant had founded a permanent settlement on the west bank of the forks of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] An admirer of Benjamin Franklin, Sullivant chose to name his frontier village "Franklinton".
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The location was desirable for its proximity to the navigable rivers – but Sullivant was initially foiled when, in 1798, a large flood wiped out the new settlement.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] He persevered, and the village was rebuilt, though somewhat more inland.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] After the Revolution, land comprising parts of Franklin and adjacent counties was set aside by Congress for settlement by Canadians and Nova Scotians who were sympathetic to the colonial cause and had their land and possessions seized by the British government.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Refugee Tract, consisting of 103,000 acres (42,000 ha), was 42 miles (68 km) long and 3–4.5 miles (4.8–7.2 km) wide, and was claimed by 67 eligible men.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Ohio Statehouse sits on land once contained in the Refugee Tract.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] After Ohio achieved statehood in 1803, political infighting among prominent Ohio leaders led to the state capital moving from Chillicothe to Zanesville and back again.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Desiring to settle on a location, the state legislature considered Franklinton, Dublin, Worthington and Delaware before compromising on a plan to build a new city in the state's center, near major transportation routes, primarily rivers.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Franklinton landowners had donated two 10-acre (4.0 ha) plots in an effort to convince the state to move its capital there.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The two spaces were set to become Capitol Square, including for the Ohio Statehouse and the Ohio Penitentiary.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Named in honor of Christopher Columbus, the city was founded on February 14, 1812, on the "High Banks opposite Franklinton at the Forks of the Scioto most known as Wolf's Ridge." At the time, this area was a dense forestland, used only as a hunting ground.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city was incorporated as a borough on February 10, 1816.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Pike served as the first appointed mayor.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Although the recent War of 1812 had brought prosperity to the area, the subsequent recession and conflicting claims to the land threatened the new town's success.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Early conditions were abysmal, with frequent bouts of fevers, attributed to malaria from the flooding rivers, and an outbreak of cholera in 1833.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It led Columbus to create the Board of Health, now part of the Columbus Public Health department.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The outbreak, which remained in the city from July to September 1833, killed 100 people.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus was without direct river or trail connections to other Ohio cities, leading to slow initial growth.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The National Road reached Columbus from Baltimore in 1831, which complemented the city's new link to the Ohio and Erie Canal, both of which facilitated a population boom.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] A wave of European immigrants led to the creation of two ethnic enclaves on the city's outskirts.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] A large Irish population settled in the north along Naghten Street (presently Nationwide Boulevard), while the Germans took advantage of the cheap land to the south, creating a community that came to be known as the *Das Alte Südende* (The Old South End).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus's German population constructed numerous breweries, Trinity Lutheran Seminary and Capital University.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] With a population of 3,500, Columbus was officially chartered as a city on March 3, 1834.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] On that day, the legislature carried out a special act, which granted legislative authority to the city council and judicial authority to the mayor.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Elections were held in April of that year, with voters choosing John Brooks as the first popularly elected mayor.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus annexed the then-separate city of Franklinton in 1837.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1850, the Columbus and Xenia Railroad became the first railroad into the city, followed by the Cleveland, Columbus and Cincinnati Railroad in 1851.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The two railroads built a joint Union Station on the east side of High Street just north of Naghten (then called North Public Lane).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Rail traffic into Columbus increased: by 1875, eight railroads served Columbus, and the rail companies built a new, more elaborate station.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Another cholera outbreak hit Columbus in 1849, prompting the opening of the city's Green Lawn Cemetery.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] On January 7, 1857, the Ohio Statehouse finally opened after 18 years of construction.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Before the abolition of slavery in the Southern United States in 1863, the Underground Railroad was active in Columbus and was led, in part, by James Preston Poindexter.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Poindexter arrived in Columbus in the 1830s and became a Baptist preacher and leader in the city's African-American community until the turn of the century.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] During the Civil War, Columbus was a major base for the volunteer Union Army.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It housed 26,000 troops and held up to 9,000 Confederate prisoners of war at Camp Chase, at what is now the Hilltop neighborhood of west Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Over 2,000 Confederate soldiers remain buried at the site, making it one of the North's largest Confederate cemeteries.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] By virtue of the Morrill Act of 1862, the Ohio Agricultural and Mechanical College – which eventually became the Ohio State University – was founded in 1870 on the former estate of William and Hannah Neil.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] By the end of the 19th century, Columbus was home to several major manufacturing businesses.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Jeffrey Manufacturing Company was a major supplier of coal mining equipment.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city became known as the "Buggy Capital of the World", thanks to the two dozen buggy factories, notably the Columbus Buggy Company, founded in 1875 by C.D.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Consolidated Brewing Company also rose to prominence during this time and might have achieved even greater success were it not for the Anti-Saloon League in neighboring Westerville.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Bush presided over the Buckeye Steel Castings Company.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus was also a popular location for labor organizations.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1886, Samuel Gompers founded the American Federation of Labor in Druid's Hall on South Fourth Street, and in 1890, the United Mine Workers of America was founded at the old City Hall.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Experiment was an environmental project in 1908 which involved construction of the first water plant in the world to apply filtration and softening, designed and invented by two brothers, Clarence and Charles Hoover.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Those working to construct the project included Jeremiah O'Shaughnessy, name-bearer of the Columbus metropolitan area's O'Shaughnessy Dam.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] This invention helped drastically reduce typhoid deaths.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The essential design is still used today.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The 1910 Columbus streetcar strike took place in downtown Columbus; the strike action turned into a violent riot, though was eventually unsuccessful.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus earned one of its nicknames, "The Arch City", because of the dozens of wooden arches that spanned High Street at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The arches illuminated the thoroughfare and eventually became the means by which electric power was provided to the new streetcars.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city tore down the arches and replaced them with cluster lights in 1914 but reconstructed them from metal in the Short North neighborhood in 2002 for their unique historical interest.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] On March 25, 1913, the Great Flood of 1913 devastated the neighborhood of Franklinton, leaving over 90 people dead and thousands of West Side residents homeless.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] To prevent flooding, the Army Corps of Engineers recommended widening the Scioto River through downtown, constructing new bridges and building a retaining wall along its banks.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] With the strength of the post-World War I economy, a construction boom occurred in the 1920s, resulting in a new civic center, the Ohio Theatre, the American Insurance Union Citadel and to the north, a massive new Ohio Stadium.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Although the American Professional Football Association was founded in Canton in 1920, its head offices moved to Columbus in 1921 to the New Hayden Building and remained in the city until 1941.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1922, the association's name was changed to the National Football League.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Nearly a decade later, in 1931, at a convention in the city, the Jehovah's Witnesses took that name by which they are known today.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The effects of the Great Depression were less severe in Columbus, as the city's diversified economy helped it fare better than its Rust Belt neighbors.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] World War II brought many new jobs and another population surge.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] This time, most new arrivals were migrants from the "extraordinarily depressed rural areas" of Appalachia, who would soon account for more than a third of Columbus's growing population.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1948, the Town and Country Shopping Center opened in suburban Whitehall, and it is now regarded as one of the first modern shopping centers in the United States.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The construction of the Interstate Highway System signaled the arrival of rapid suburb development in central Ohio.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] To protect the city's tax base from this suburbanization, Columbus adopted a policy of linking sewer and water hookups to annexation to the city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] By the early 1990s, Columbus had grown to become Ohio's largest city in land area and in population.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Efforts to revitalize downtown Columbus have had some success in recent decades, though like most major American cities, some architectural heritage was lost in the process.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 1970s, landmarks such as Union Station and the Neil House hotel were razed to construct high-rise offices and big retail space.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The PNC Bank building was constructed in 1977, as well as the Nationwide Plaza buildings and other towers that sprouted during this period.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The construction of the Greater Columbus Convention Center has brought major conventions and trade shows to the city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] AmeriFlora '92 was held in the city in 1992, part of the Christopher Columbus Quincentennial Jubilee, celebrating the 500th anniversary of Columbus's first voyage.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The organizers also planned to create a replica Native American village, among other attractions.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Local and national native leaders protested the event with a day of mourning, followed by protests and fasts at City Hall.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The protests prevented the native village from being exhibited.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] A protest also took place during the dedication of the *Santa Maria* replica, an event held in late 1991 on the day before Columbus Day and in time for the jubilee.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1999, just before the turn of the 21st century, the city's first African American mayor was elected.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Michael Coleman, a Democrat, served 16 years, the longest of any mayor of the city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Coleman's administration led to Nationwide Insurance redeveloping the former Ohio Penitentiary site and nearby blocks into the Arena District.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Similar new construction and redevelopment was taking place in the Brewery District, and a flood wall was completed in Franklinton in 2004, finally letting development resume in the neighborhood.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Scioto Mile began development along the riverfront, an area that already had the Miranova Corporate Center and The Condominiums at North Bank Park.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The 2010 United States foreclosure crisis forced the city to purchase numerous foreclosed, vacant properties to renovate or demolish them at a cost of tens of millions of dollars.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city is focused on downtown revitalization, with recent projects being the Columbus Commons park, parks along the Scioto Mile developed along with a reshaped riverfront, and developments in the Arena District and Franklinton.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Columbus began when the city reported its first official cases of COVID-19 in February and March 2020 and declared a state of emergency.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Later in 2020, protests over the murder of George Floyd occurred in the city from May 28 into August.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In November 2024, about a dozen masked men dressed in black carried red swastika flags in Columbus chanting racial slurs and using pepper spray.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In July 2024, Columbus was subject to a ransomware attack, for which the hacker group Rhysidia took credit.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In August 2024, Columbus Mayor Andrew Ginther claimed that the files obtained by Rhysidia were "unusable" to the thieves due to being either encrypted or corrupted.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Ginther's assertion was subsequently shown to be false by security researcher David Leroy Ross, who revealed that the files were intact and contained data including names from domestic violence cases and Social Security numbers of crime victims.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus then sued Ross for alleged criminal acts, negligence, and civil conversion, as well as taking out a restraining order against Ross, both of which actions were later defended by City Attorney Zach Klein.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In response, a number of prominent cybersecurity researchers called on the city to drop the lawsuit.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 2020s, the city became a center for high technology, innovation, and high-tech manufacturing, particularly in artificial intelligence, robotics, and semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2023, Intel announced plans to construct a $20 billion factory and Honda expanding its presence along with LG Energy Solutions with a $4.4 billion battery manufactory facility in Fayette County.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In January 2025, Anduril announced a series of Arsenal Projects, hyperscaling computer facilities for autonomous weapons.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] They also announced the construction of a manufacturing facility in Columbus, to be named "Arsenal-1", with subsequent Arsenals planned.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] This facility will be designed to be able to manufacture advanced systems faster than near peer manufacturers.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It is noted for its close ties with Ohio State University, with Anduril Industries sponsoring the football program for the 2025 to 2026 year, connections to the college administration, and much of Anduril-1's employees hailing from its applied science programs.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The confluence of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers is just northwest of Downtown Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Several smaller tributaries course through the Columbus metropolitan area, including Alum Creek, Big Walnut Creek and Darby Creek.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is considered to have relatively flat topography thanks to a large glacier that covered most of Ohio during the Wisconsin Ice Age.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] However, there are sizable differences in elevation through the area, with the high point of Franklin County being 1,132 feet (345 meters) above sea level near New Albany, and the low point being 670 ft (200 m) where the Scioto River leaves the county near Lockbourne.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Several ravines near the rivers and creeks also add variety to the landscape.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Tributaries to Alum Creek and the Olentangy River cut through shale, while tributaries to the Scioto River cut through limestone.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The numerous rivers and streams beside low-lying areas in Central Ohio contribute to a history of flooding in the region; the most significant was the Great Flood of 1913 in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city has a total area of 223.11 square miles (577.9 square kilometers), of which 217.17 sq mi (562.5 km2) is land and 5.94 sq mi (15.4 km2) is water.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has the largest land area of any Ohio city; this is due to Jim Rhodes's tactic to annex suburbs while serving as mayor.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] As surrounding communities grew or were constructed, they came to require access to waterlines, which was under the sole control of the municipal water system.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Rhodes told these communities that if they wanted water, they would have to submit to assimilation into Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has a wide diversity of neighborhoods with different characters, and is thus sometimes known as a "city of neighborhoods".
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Some of the most prominent neighborhoods include the Arena District, the Brewery District, Clintonville, Franklinton, German Village, The Short North and Victorian Village.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's climate is humid continental (Köppen climate classification *Dfa*) transitional with the humid subtropical (Köppen climate classification *Cfa*) to the south characterized by warm, muggy summers and cold, dry winters.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is within USDA hardiness zone 6b, bordering on 7a.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Winter snowfall is relatively light, since the city is not in the typical path of strong winter lows, such as the Nor'easters that strike cities farther east.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It is also too far south and west for lake-effect snow from Lake Erie to have much effect, although the lakes to the north contribute to long stretches of cloudy spells in winter.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The highest temperature recorded in Columbus is 106 °F (41 °C), which occurred twice during the Dust Bowl of the 1930s: once on July 21, 1934, and again on July 14, 1936.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The lowest recorded temperature was −22 °F (−30 °C), occurring on January 19, 1994.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is subject to severe weather typical to the Midwestern United States.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Severe thunderstorms can bring lightning, large hail and on rare occasions tornadoes, especially during the spring and sometimes through fall.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] A tornado that occurred on October 11, 2006, caused F2 damage.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Floods, blizzards and ice storms can also occur from time to time.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has focused on reducing its environmental impact and carbon footprint.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2020, a citywide ballot measure was approved, giving Columbus an electricity aggregation plan which will supply it with 100% renewable energy by the start of 2023.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Its vendor, AEP Energy, plans to construct new wind and solar farms in Ohio to help supply the electricity.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The largest sources of pollution in the county, as of 2019, are Ohio State University's McCracken Power Plant, the landfill operated by the Solid Waste Authority of Central Ohio (SWACO) and the Anheuser-Busch Columbus Brewery.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Anheuser-Busch has a company-wide goal of reducing emissions by 25% by 2025.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Ohio State plans to construct a new heat and power plant, also powered by fossil fuels, but set to reduce emissions by about 30%.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] SWACO manages to capture 75% of its methane emissions to use in producing energy, and is looking to reduce emissions further.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] As of the 2020 census, Columbus had a population of 905,748.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] 21.9% of residents were under the age of 18 and 11.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] For every 100 females there were 95.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 93.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] 99.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] There were 382,038 households in Columbus, of which 26.5% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Of all households, 31.4% were married-couple households, 25.2% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.1% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] About 35.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] There were 415,456 housing units, of which 8.0% were vacant.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.2%.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus historically had a significant population of white people.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1900, whites made up 93.4% of the population.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Although European immigration has declined, the Columbus metropolitan area has recently experienced increases in African, Asian and Latin American immigration, including groups from Mexico, India, Nepal, Bhutan, Somalia and China.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] While the Asian population is diverse, the city's Hispanic community is mainly made up of Mexican Americans, although there is a notable Puerto Rican population.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Many other countries of origin are represented in lesser numbers, largely due to the international draw of Ohio State University.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] 2008 estimates indicate that roughly 116,000 of the city's residents are foreign-born, accounting for 82% of the new residents between 2000 and 2006 at a rate of 105 per week.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] 40% of the immigrants came from Asia, 23% from Africa, 22% from Latin America and 13% from Europe.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city had the second-largest Somali and Somali American population in the country, as of 2004, as well as the largest expatriate Bhutanese-Nepali population in the world, as of 2018.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Due to its demographics, which include a mix of races and a wide range of incomes, as well as urban, suburban and nearby rural areas, Columbus is considered a "typical" American city, leading retail and restaurant chains to use it as a test market for new products.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] For similar reasons, the city was chosen as the launch city for the QUBE cable television service.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has maintained a steady population growth since its establishment.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Its slowest growth, from 1850 to 1860, is primarily attributed to the city's cholera epidemic in the 1850s.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] According to the 2017 Japanese Direct Investment Survey by the Consulate-General of Japan, Detroit, 838 Japanese nationals lived in Columbus, making it the municipality with the state's second-largest Japanese national population, after Dublin.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is home to a proportional LGBT community, with an estimated 34,952 gay, lesbian or bisexual residents.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The 2018 American Community Survey (ACS) reported an estimated 366,034 households, 32,276 of which were held by unmarried partners.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] 1,395 of these were female householder and female-partner households, and 1,456 were male householder and male-partner households.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has been rated as one of the best cities in the country for gays and lesbians to live, and also as the most underrated gay city in the country.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Stonewall Columbus formed in 1981 after a group of protestors organized a march against a proposed office of Moral Majority, a political organization lead by pastor Jerry Falwell, Sr.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The next year, Stonewall hosted its first Pride Parade.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In July 2012, three years prior to legal same-sex marriage in the United States, the Columbus City Council unanimously passed a domestic partnership registry.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has numerous Italian Americans, with groups including the Columbus Italian Club, Columbus Piave Club and the Abruzzi Club.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Italian Village, a neighborhood near Downtown Columbus, has had a prominent Italian American community since the 1890s.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The community has helped promote the influence Christopher Columbus had in drawing European attention to the Americas.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Italian explorer, erroneously credited with the lands' discovery, has been posthumously criticized by historians for initiating colonization and for abuse, enslavement and subjugation of natives.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In addition to the city being named for the explorer, its seal and flag depict a ship he used for his first voyage to the Americas, the *Santa María*.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] A similar-size replica of the ship, the Santa Maria Ship & Museum, was displayed downtown from 1991 to 2014.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's Discovery District and Discovery Bridge are named in reference to Columbus's "discovery" of the Americas; the bridge includes artistic bronze medallions featuring symbols of the explorer.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Genoa Park, downtown, is named after Genoa, the birthplace of Christopher Columbus and one of Columbus's sister cities.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Christopher Columbus Quincentennial Jubilee, celebrating the 500th anniversary of Columbus's first voyage, was held in the city in 1992.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Its organizers spent $95 million on it, creating the horticultural exhibition AmeriFlora '92.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The protests prevented the native village from being exhibited, and annual fasts continued until 1997.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city has three outdoor statues of the explorer; the statue at City Hall was acquired, delivered and dedicated with the assistance of the Italian American community.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Protests in 2017 aimed for this statue to be removed, followed by the city in 2018 ceasing to recognize Columbus Day as a city holiday.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] During the 2020 George Floyd protests, petitions were created to remove all three statues and rename the city of Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city was one of eight cities to be offered the 360 ft (110 m) *Birth of the New World* statue, in 1993.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The statue, also of Christopher Columbus, was completed in Puerto Rico in 2016 and is the tallest in the United States – 45 ft (14 m) taller than the Statue of Liberty, including its pedestal.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] At least six U.S. cities, including Columbus, rejected it based on its height and design.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] According to the 2019 American Values Atlas, 26% of Columbus metropolitan area residents are unaffiliated with a religious tradition.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] 17% of area residents identify as White evangelical Protestants, 14% as White mainline Protestants, 11% as Black Protestants, 11% as White Catholics, 5% as Hispanic Catholics, 3% as other nonwhite Catholics, 2% as other nonwhite Protestants and 2% as Mormons.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Hindus, Buddhists, Jews and Latino Protestants each made up 1% of the population, while Jehovah's Witnesses, Orthodox Christians, Muslims, Unitarians, and members of New Age or other religions each made up under 0.5% of the population.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has a generally strong and diverse economy based on education, insurance, banking, fashion, defense, aviation, food, logistics, steel, energy, medical research, health care, hospitality, retail and technology.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2010, it was one of the 10 best big cities in the country, according to Relocate America, a real estate research firm.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] According to the Federal Reserve Bank of St.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Louis, the GDP of Columbus in 2019 was $134 billion (~$162 billion in 2024).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] During the Great Recession between 2007 and 2009, Columbus's economy was not impacted as much as the rest of the country, due to decades of diversification work by long-time corporate residents, business leaders and political leaders.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The administration of former mayor Michael B.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Coleman continued this work, although the city faced financial turmoil and had to increase taxes, allegedly due in part to fiscal mismanagement.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Because Columbus is the state capital, there is a large government presence in the city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Including city, county, state and federal employers, government jobs provide the largest single source of employment within Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2019, the city had six corporations named to the U.S.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Fortune 500 list: Alliance Data, Nationwide Mutual Insurance Company, American Electric Power, L Brands, Huntington Bancshares and Cardinal Health in suburban Dublin.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Fast-food chains Wendy's and White Castle are also headquartered in the Columbus area.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Major foreign corporations operating or with divisions in the city include Germany-based Siemens and Roxane Laboratories, Finland-based Vaisala, Tomasco Mulciber Inc., A Y Manufacturing, as well as Switzerland-based ABB and Mettler Toledo.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city also has a significant fashion and retail presence, home to companies such as Big Lots, L Brands, Abercrombie & Fitch, DSW and Express.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] North Market, a public market and food hall, is located downtown near the Short North.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It is the only remaining public market of Columbus's original four marketplaces.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus-style pizza features a thin crust and a slightly sweet tomato sauce.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The cheese, usually mozzarella or provolone, fully covers the crust without leaving any bare areas.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The pizza is round but is cut into squares.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Numerous restaurant chains are based in the Columbus area, including Charleys Philly Steaks, Bibibop Asian Grill, Steak Escape, White Castle, Cameron Mitchell Restaurants, Bob Evans Restaurants, Max & Erma's, Damon's Grill, Donatos Pizza and Wendy's.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Wendy's, the world's third-largest hamburger fast-food chain, operated its first store downtown as both a museum and a restaurant until March 2007, when the establishment was closed due to low revenue.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The company is presently headquartered outside the city in nearby Dublin.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Budweiser has a major brewery located on the north side, just south of I-270 and Worthington.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is also home to many local micro breweries and pubs.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Asian frozen food manufacturer Kahiki Foods was located on the east side of Columbus, created during the operation of the Kahiki Supper Club restaurant in Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The food company now operates in the suburb of Gahanna and has been owned by the South Korean-based company CJ CheilJedang since 2018.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Wasserstrom Company, a major supplier of equipment and supplies for restaurants, is located on the north side.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has over 170 notable buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places; it also maintains its own register, the Columbus Register of Historic Properties, with 82 entries.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city also maintains four historic districts not listed on its register: German Village, Italian Village, Victorian Village, and the Brewery District.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Construction of the Ohio Statehouse began in 1839 on a 10-acre (4 ha) plot of land donated by four prominent Columbus landowners.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] This plot formed Capitol Square, which was not part of the city's original layout.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Built of Columbus limestone from the Marble Cliff Quarry Co., the Statehouse stands on foundations 18 feet (5.5 m) deep that were laid by prison labor gangs rumored to have been composed largely of masons jailed for minor infractions.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It features several artworks within and outside the building, including the *William McKinley Monument* dedicated in 1907.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Within the Driving Park heritage district lies the original home of Eddie Rickenbacker, a World War I fighter pilot ace.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Built in 1895, the house was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Preservationists and the public have sometimes run into conflict with developers hoping to revitalize an area and demolish certain buildings, and historically with the city and state government, which led programs of urban renewal in the 20th century.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has a wide variety of museums and galleries.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Its primary art museum is the Columbus Museum of Art, which operates its main location as well as the Pizzuti Collection, featuring contemporary art.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The museum, founded in 1878, focuses on European and American art up to early modernism that includes extraordinary examples of Impressionism, German Expressionism and Cubism.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Another prominent art museum in the city is the Wexner Center for the Arts, a contemporary art gallery and research facility operated by the Ohio State University.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Ohio History Connection is headquartered in Columbus, with its flagship museum, the 250,000-square-foot (23,000 m2) Ohio History Center, 4 mi (6.4 km) north of downtown.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Adjacent to the museum is Ohio Village, a replica of a village around the time of the American Civil War.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Historical Society also features historical exhibits, which focus more closely on life in Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] COSI is a large science and children's museum in downtown Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The present building, the former Central High School, was completed in November 1999, opposite downtown on the west bank of the Scioto River.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2009, *Parents* magazine named COSI one of the 10 best science centers for families in the country.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Other science museums include the Orton Geological Museum and the Museum of Biological Diversity, which are both part of Ohio State University.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Franklin Park Conservatory is the city's botanical garden, which opened in 1895.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] It features over 400 species of plants in a large Victorian-style glass greenhouse building that includes rain forest, desert and Himalayan mountain biomes.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The National Veterans Memorial and Museum, which opened in 2018, focuses on the personal stories of military veterans throughout U.S. history.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The museum replaced the Franklin County Veterans Memorial, which opened in 1955.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Other notable museums in the city include the Central Ohio Fire Museum, Billy Ireland Cartoon Library & Museum and the Ohio Craft Museum.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is the home of many performing arts institutions including the Columbus Symphony Orchestra, Opera Columbus, BalletMet Columbus, the ProMusica Chamber Orchestra, The Contemporary Theatre of Ohio, Columbus Children's Theatre, Shadowbox Live, and the Columbus Jazz Orchestra.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Throughout the summer, the Actors' Theatre of Columbus offers free performances of Shakespearean plays in an open-air amphitheater in Schiller Park in historic German Village.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Youth Ballet Academy was founded in the 1980s by ballerina and artistic director Shir Lee Wu, a discovery of Martha Graham.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Wu was the long-time artistic director of the Columbus City Ballet School and taught classes there until her death in 2021.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has several large concert venues, including the Nationwide Arena, Value City Arena, Express Live!, Mershon Auditorium and the Newport Music Hall.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] In May 2009, the Lincoln Theatre, formerly a center for Black culture in Columbus, reopened after an extensive restoration.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Not far from the Lincoln Theatre is the King Arts Complex, which hosts a variety of cultural events.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The city also has several theaters downtown, including the historic Palace Theatre, the Ohio Theatre and the Southern Theatre.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] Broadway Across America often presents touring Broadway musicals in these larger venues.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The Vern Riffe Center for Government and the Arts houses the Capitol Theatre and three smaller studio theaters, providing a home for resident performing arts companies.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p01] The 2018 film *Ready Player One* is set in Columbus, though not filmed in the city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus hosts two major league professional sports teams: the Columbus Blue Jackets of the National Hockey League (NHL), which play at Nationwide Arena, and the Columbus Crew of Major League Soccer (MLS), which play at ScottsMiracle-Gro Field.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Crew previously played at Historic Crew Stadium, the first soccer-specific stadium built in the United States for a Major League Soccer team.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Crew were one of the original members of MLS and won their first MLS Cup in 2008, a second title in 2020, and a third title in 2023.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Crew moved into then named Lower.com Field in the summer of 2021, which will also feature a mixed-use development site named Confluence Village.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] ScottsMiracle-Gro Field will host a total of nine Olympic soccer matches during the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Clippers, the International League affiliate of the Cleveland Guardians, play in Huntington Park, which opened in 2009.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city was home to the Panhandles/Tigers football team from 1901 to 1926; they are credited with playing in the first NFL game against another NFL opponent.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In the late 1990s, the Columbus Quest won the only two championships during American Basketball League's two-and-a-half season existence.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Ohio Aviators were based in Obetz, Ohio, and began play in the only PRO Rugby season before the league folded.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] From 1883 to 1884, Columbus was the home of the Columbus Buckeyes of Major League Baseball, who played two seasons in the American Association before folding operations after the 1884 season.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Since 2023, Columbus has been home to the Columbus Fury women's professional volleyball team, one of seven teams to launch with the Pro Volleyball Federation.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The team plays home games at Nationwide Arena.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus NWSL team will begin play in 2028.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is home to one of the nation's most competitive intercollegiate programs, the Ohio State Buckeyes of Ohio State University.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The program has placed in the top 10 final standings of the Director's Cup five times since 2000–2001, including No.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The university funds 36 varsity teams, consisting of 17 male, 16 female and three co-educational teams.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2007–2008 and 2008–2009, the program generated the second-most revenue for college programs behind the Texas Longhorns of The University of Texas at Austin.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Ohio State Buckeyes are a member of the NCAA's Big Ten Conference, and their football team plays home games at Ohio Stadium.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Ohio State–Michigan football game (known colloquially as "The Game") is the final game of the regular season and is played in November each year, alternating between Columbus and Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2000, ESPN ranked the Ohio State–Michigan game as the greatest rivalry in North American sports.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Moreover, "Buckeye fever" permeates Columbus culture year-round and forms a major part of Columbus's cultural identity.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] During the winter months, the Buckeyes basketball and hockey teams are also major sporting attractions.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus has a long history in motorsports, hosting the world's first 24-hour car race at the Columbus Driving Park in 1905, which was organized by the Columbus Auto Club.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Motor Speedway was built in 1945 and held its first motorcycle race in 1946.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2010, the Ohio State University student-built Buckeye Bullet 2, a fuel-cell vehicle, set an FIA world speed record for electric vehicles in reaching 303.025 mph, eclipsing the previous record of 302.877 mph.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The annual All American Quarter Horse Congress, the world's largest single-breed horse show, attracts approximately 500,000 visitors to the Ohio Expo Center each October.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus hosts the annual Arnold Sports Festival.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Hosted by Arnold Schwarzenegger, the event has grown to eight Olympic sports and 22,000 athletes competing in 80 events.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Westside Barbell, a world-renowned powerlifting gym, is located in Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Its founder, Louie Simmons, is known for his popularization of the "Conjugate Method", while he is also credited with inventing training machines for reverse hyper-extensions and belt squats.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Westside Barbell is known for producing multiple world record holders in powerlifting.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Bullies were two-time champions of the American Football League (1940–1941).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Ohio Roller Derby (formerly Ohio Roller Girls) was founded in Columbus in 2005 and still competes internationally in Women's Flat Track Derby Association play.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The team is regularly ranked in the top 60 internationally.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus's Recreation and Parks Department oversees about 370 city parks.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Also in the area are 19 regional parks and the Metro Parks, which are part of the Columbus and Franklin County Metropolitan Park District.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] These parks include Clintonville's Whetstone Park and the Columbus Park of Roses, a 13-acre (5.3 ha) rose garden.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Chadwick Arboretum on Ohio State's campus features a large and varied collection of plants, while its Olentangy River Wetland Research Park is an experimental wetland open to the public.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Downtown, the painting *A Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte* is represented in topiary at Columbus's Topiary Park.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Also near downtown, the Scioto Audubon Metro Park on the Whittier Peninsula opened in 2009 and includes a large Audubon nature center focused on the birdwatching the area is known for.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Zoo and Aquarium's collections include lowland gorillas, polar bears, manatees, Siberian tigers, cheetahs and kangaroos.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Also in the zoo complex is the Zoombezi Bay water park and amusement park.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Annual festivities in Columbus include the Ohio State Fair – one of the largest state fairs in the country – as well as the Columbus Arts Festival and the Jazz & Rib Fest, both of which occur on the downtown riverfront.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In mid-May from 2007 to 2018, Columbus was home to Rock on the Range, which was held at Historic Crew Stadium and marketed as America's biggest rock festival.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The festival, which took place on a Friday, Saturday and Sunday, has hosted Metallica, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Slipknot and other notable bands.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In May 2019, it was officially replaced by the Sonic Temple Art & Music Festival.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] During the first weekend in June, the bars of Columbus's North Market District host the Park Street Festival, which attracts thousands of visitors to a massive party in bars and on the street.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] June's second-to-last weekend sees one of the Midwest's largest gay pride parades, Columbus Pride, reflecting the city's sizable gay population.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's largest dining event, Restaurant Week Columbus, is held twice a year in mid-January and mid-July.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2010, more than 40,000 diners went to 40 participating restaurants, and $5,000 (~$7,382 in 2025) was donated the Mid-Ohio Foodbank on behalf of sponsors and participating restaurants.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Around the Fourth of July, Columbus hosts Red, White, and Boom! on the Scioto riverfront downtown, attracting crowds of over 500,000 people and featuring the largest fireworks display in the Midwest.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The namesake of similar celebrations nationwide, the first originated in Columbus in 1981.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Short North is host to the monthly Gallery Hop, which attracts hundreds to the neighborhood's art galleries (which all open their doors to the public until late at night) and street musicians.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Hilltop Bean Dinner is an annual event held on Columbus's West Side that celebrates the city's Civil War heritage near the historic Camp Chase Cemetery.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] At the end of September, German Village throws an annual Oktoberfest celebration that features German food, beer, music and crafts.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus also hosts many conventions in the Greater Columbus Convention Center, a large convention center on the north edge of downtown.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Completed in 1993, the 1.8-million-square-foot (170,000 m2) convention center was designed by architect Peter Eisenman, who also designed the Wexner Center.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Both of the metropolitan area's major shopping centers are located in Columbus: Easton Town Center and Polaris Fashion Place.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Jacobs built the area's first three major shopping malls in the 1960s: Westland, Northland and Eastland.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Near Northland Mall was The Continent, an open-air mall in the Northland area, mostly vacant and pending redevelopment.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus City Center was built downtown in 1988, alongside the first location of Lazarus; this mall closed in 2009 and was demolished in 2011.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Easton Town Center was built in 1999 and Polaris Fashion Place in 2001.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city is administered by a mayor and a nine-member unicameral Columbus City Council elected in two classes every two years to four-year terms at large.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is the largest city in the United States that elects its city council at large as opposed to districts.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The mayor appoints the director of safety and the director of public service.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The people elect the auditor, municipal court clerk, municipal court judges and city attorney.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] A charter commission, elected in 1913, submitted a new charter in May 1914, offering a modified federal form, with a number of progressive features, such as nonpartisan ballot, preferential voting, recall of elected officials, the referendum and a small council elected at large.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The charter was adopted, effective January 1, 1916.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Andrew Ginther has been the mayor of Columbus since 2016.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] As Ohio's capital and the county seat, Columbus hosts numerous federal, state, county and city government offices and courts.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Courthouse, one of several courts for the District Court for the Southern District of Ohio, after moving from 121 E.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Bricker Federal Building, has offices for U.S.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Senator Sherrod Brown, as well as for the Internal Revenue Service, the Social Security Administration and the Departments of Housing & Urban Development and Agriculture.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The State of Ohio's capitol building, the Ohio Statehouse, is located in the center of downtown on Capitol Square.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] It houses the Ohio House of Representatives and Ohio Senate.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] It also contains the ceremonial offices of the governor, lieutenant governor, state treasurer and state auditor.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Supreme Court, Court of Claims and Judicial Conference are located in the Thomas J.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Moyer Ohio Judicial Center downtown by the Scioto River.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The building, built in 1933 to house 10 state agencies along with the State Library of Ohio, became the Supreme Court after extensive renovations from 2001 to 2004.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Franklin County operates the Franklin County Government Center, a complex at the southern end of downtown Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The center includes the county's municipal court, common pleas court, correctional center, juvenile detention center and sheriff's office.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Coleman Government Center holds offices for the departments of building and zoning services, public service, development and public utilities.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Also nearby is 77 North Front Street, which holds Columbus's city attorney office, income-tax division, public safety, human resources, civil service and purchasing departments.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The structure, built in 1929, was the police headquarters until 1991, and was then dormant until it was given a $34 million renovation from 2011 to 2013.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Municipal police duties are performed by the Columbus Division of Police, while emergency medical services (EMS) and fire protection are through the Columbus Division of Fire.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Ohio Homeland Security operates the Strategic Analysis and Information Center (SAIC) fusion center in Columbus's Hilltop neighborhood.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The facility is the state's primary public intelligence hub and one of the few in the country that uses state, local, federal and private resources.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus has a history of governmental and nonprofit support for low-income residents and the homeless.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Nevertheless, the homelessness rate has steadily risen since at least 2007.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Poverty and differences in quality of life have grown, as well; Columbus was noted as the second-most economically segregated large metropolitan area in 2015, in a study by the University of Toronto.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] It also ranked 45th of the 50 largest metropolitan areas in terms of social mobility, according to a 2015 Harvard University study.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is the home of two public colleges: the Ohio State University, one of the largest college campuses in the United States, and Columbus State Community College.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2009, Ohio State University was ranked No.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] News & World Report* on its list of best public universities, and No.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] 56 overall, scoring in the first tier of schools nationally.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Some of Ohio State's graduate school programs placed in the top 5, including No.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] 5 for both best veterinary programs and best pharmacy programs.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The specialty graduate programs of social psychology was ranked No.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] 2, and elementary education, secondary teacher education, administration/supervision was No.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Three major suburban schools also have an influence on Columbus's educational landscape: Bexley's Capital University, Westerville's Otterbein University and Delaware's Ohio Wesleyan University.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus City Schools (CCS) is the largest district in Ohio, with 55,000 pupils.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] CCS operates 142 elementary, middle and high schools, including a number of magnet schools (which are referred to as alternative schools within the school system).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The suburbs operate their own districts, typically serving students in one or more townships, with districts sometimes crossing municipal boundaries.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Roman Catholic Diocese of Columbus also operates several parochial elementary and high schools.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The area's second-largest school district is South-Western City Schools, which encompasses southwestern Franklin County, including a slice of Columbus itself.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Other portions of Columbus are zoned to the Dublin, Hilliard, New Albany-Plain, Westerville and Worthington school districts.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] There are also several private schools in the area, such as St.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Paul's Lutheran School, a K-8 Christian school of the Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod in Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Some sources determine that the first kindergarten in the United States was established here by Louisa Frankenberg, a former student of Friedrich Fröbel.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Frankenberg immigrated to the city in 1838 and opened her kindergarten in the German Village neighborhood in that year.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The school did not work out, so she returned to Germany in 1840.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 1858, Frankenberg returned to Columbus and established another early kindergarten in the city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Frankenberg is often overlooked, with Margarethe Schurz instead given credit for her "First Kindergarten" she operated for two years.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In addition, Indianola Junior High School (now the Graham Elementary and Middle School) became the nation's first junior high school in 1909, helping to bridge the difficult transition from elementary to high school at a time when only 48% of students continued their education after the ninth grade.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Metropolitan Library (CML) has served central Ohio residents since 1873.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The system has 23 locations throughout Central Ohio, with a total collection of 3 million items.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] This library is one of the country's most-used library systems and is consistently among the top-ranked large city libraries according to Hennen's American Public Library Ratings.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] 1 library system in the nation in 1999, 2005 and 2008.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] It has been in the top four every year since 1999, when the rankings were first published in the *American Libraries* magazine, often challenging upstate neighbor Cuyahoga County Public Library for the top spot.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The classes of the Columbus Japanese Language School, a weekend Japanese school, are held in a facility from the school district in Marysville, while the school office is in Worthington.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Previously it held classes at facilities in the city of Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Several weekly and daily newspapers serve Columbus and Central Ohio.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The major daily newspaper in Columbus is *The Columbus Dispatch*.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] There are also neighborhood- or suburb-specific papers, such as the Dispatch Printing Company's *ThisWeek Community News*, the *Columbus Messenger*, the *Clintonville Spotlight* and the *Short North Gazette*.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] *The Lantern* and *1870* serve the Ohio State University community.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Alternative arts, culture or politics-oriented papers include *ALIVE* (formerly the independent *Columbus Alive* and now owned by the *Columbus Dispatch*), *Columbus Free Press* and *Columbus Underground* (digital-only).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The *Columbus Magazine*, *CityScene*, *614 Magazine* and *Columbus Monthly* are the city's magazines.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is the base for 12 television stations and is the 32nd-largest television market as of September 24, 2016.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is also home to the 36th-largest radio market.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Numerous medical systems operate in Columbus and Central Ohio.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Hospitals in Central Ohio are ranked favorably by the *U.S.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] News & World Report*, where numerous hospitals are ranked as among the best in particular fields in the United States.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Nationwide Children's is regarded as among the top 10 children's hospitals in the country, according to the report.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Electricity is distributed by Columbus Southern Power, an American Electric Power subsidiary.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Natural gas is provided by Columbia Gas of Ohio, while water is sourced from the City of Columbus Division of Water.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus's street system centers on its two main historic corridors, Broad and High Streets, which extend beyond the city limits; High Street is the longest in Columbus, running 13.5 mi (21.7 km) (23.4 across the county), while Broad Street is longer across the county, at 25.1 mi (40.4 km).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The street grid originates downtown, with High Street running north–south and Broad Street east–west; north–south streets are aligned 12 degrees west of due north, while avenues run similarly offset from due east–west.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's address system begins at the intersection of Broad and High, with numbers increasing outward and even numbers on the north and east sides of streets.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Numbered avenues start 1+1⁄4 mi (2.0 km) north of Broad, while numbered streets begin around High Street and progress eastward.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] A difference of 700 house numbers equates to about 1 mi (1.6 km).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Other significant roads include Main Street, Morse Road, SR-161 (Dublin-Granville Road), SR-3 (Cleveland Avenue/Westerville Road), and Olentangy River Road.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is bisected by two major Interstate Highways: Interstate 70 running east–west and Interstate 71 running north to roughly southwest.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] They combine downtown for about 1.5 mi (2.4 km) in an area locally known as "The Split", which is a major traffic congestion point, especially during rush hour.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Route 40, originally known as the National Road, runs east–west through Columbus, comprising Main Street to the east of downtown and Broad Street to the west.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Route 23 runs roughly north–south, while U.S.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Due to its central location within Ohio and abundance of outbound roadways, nearly all of the state's destinations are within a two- or three-hour drive of Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus riverfront hosts several bridges.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Discovery Bridge connects downtown to Franklinton across Broad Street.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The bridge opened in 1992, replacing a 1921 concrete arch bridge; the first bridge at the site was built in 1816.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The 700 ft (210 m) Main Street Bridge opened on July 30, 2010.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The bridge has three lanes for vehicular traffic (one westbound and two eastbound) and another separated lane for pedestrians and bikes.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Rich Street Bridge opened in July 2012 adjacent to the Main Street Bridge, connecting Rich Street on the east side of the river with Town Street on the west.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Lane Avenue Bridge is a cable-stayed bridge that opened on November 14, 2003, in the University District.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's primary airport, John Glenn Columbus International Airport, is on the city's east side.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Formerly known as Port Columbus, John Glenn provides service to Toronto, Ontario, Canada, and Cancun, Mexico (on a seasonal basis), as well as to most domestic destinations, including all the major hubs along with San Francisco, Salt Lake City and Seattle.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The airport was a hub for discount carrier Skybus Airlines and continues to be home to NetJets, the world's largest fractional ownership air carrier.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] According to a 2005 market survey, John Glenn Columbus International Airport attracts about 50% of its passengers from outside of its 60-mile (97 km) radius primary service region.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] It is the 52nd-busiest airport in the United States by total passenger boardings.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Rickenbacker International Airport, in southern Franklin County, is a major cargo facility that is used by the Ohio Air National Guard.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Allegiant Air offers nonstop service from Rickenbacker to Florida destinations.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Ohio State University Don Scott Airport and Bolton Field are other large general-aviation facilities in the Columbus area.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 1907, 14-year-old Cromwell Dixon built the *SkyCycle,* a pedal-powered blimp, which he flew at Driving Park.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Three years later, one of the Wright brothers' exhibition pilots, Phillip Parmalee, conducted the world's first commercial cargo flight when he flew two packages containing 88 kilograms of silk 70 miles (110 km) from Dayton to Columbus in a Wright Model B.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] During World War I, six Columbus pilots, led by ace Eddie Rickenbacker, accounted for 10% of U.S. aerial victories, more than the aviators of any other American city.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] After the war, Columbus became a key hub in a transcontinental air-rail system, with Port Columbus Airport opening in 1929 following advocacy by Charles Lindbergh.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The inaugural TAT flight included Amelia Earhart, with Henry Ford and Harvey Firestone attending.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 1964, Columbus native Jerrie Mock became the first woman to fly solo around the world, setting a speed record in her plane, the *Spirit of Columbus*.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus maintains a widespread municipal bus service called the Central Ohio Transit Authority (COTA).
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The service operates 41 routes with a fleet of 440 buses, serving approximately 19 million passengers per year.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] COTA operates 23 regular fixed-service routes, 14 express services, a bus rapid transit route, a free downtown circulator, night service, an airport connector and other services.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] LinkUS, an initiative between COTA, the city, and the Mid-Ohio Regional Planning Commission, is planning to add more rapid transit to Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Intercity bus service is provided at the Columbus Bus Station by Greyhound, Barons Bus Lines, Miller Transportation, GoBus and other carriers.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus does not have passenger rail service.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's major train station, Union Station, was a stop along Amtrak's National Limited train service until 1977 and was razed in 1979, and the Greater Columbus Convention Center now stands in its place.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The station was also a stop along the Pennsylvania Railroad, the New York Central Railroad, the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, the Norfolk and Western Railway, the Cleveland, Columbus and Cincinnati Railroad, and the Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] As the city lacks local, commuter or intercity trains, Columbus is now the largest city and metropolitan area in the U.S. without any passenger rail service.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Cycling as transportation is steadily increasing in Columbus with its relatively flat terrain, intact urban neighborhoods, large student population and off-road bike paths.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city has put forth the 2012 Bicentennial Bikeways Plan, as well as a move toward a Complete Streets policy.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Grassroots efforts such as Bike to Work Week, Consider Biking, Yay Bikes, Third Hand Bicycle Co-op, Franklinton Cycleworks and *Cranksters*, a local radio program focused on urban cycling, have contributed to cycling as transportation.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The Main Street Bridge, opened in 2010, features a dedicated bike and pedestrian lane separated from traffic.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city also has its own public bicycle system.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] CoGo Bike Share has a network of about 600 bicycles and 80 docking stations.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] PBSC Urban Solutions, a company based in Canada, supplies technology and equipment.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Bird electric scooters have also been introduced.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The city of Columbus has a higher-than-average percentage of households without a car.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2015, 9.8% of Columbus households lacked a car, a number that fell slightly to 9.4% in 2016.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus averaged 1.55 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus has 10 sister cities as designated by Sister Cities International.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus established its first sister city relationship in 1955 with Genoa, Italy.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] To commemorate this relationship, Columbus received as a gift from the people of Genoa, a bronze statue of Christopher Columbus.
[src:columbus-ohio/columbus-ohio-p02] The statue overlooked Broad Street in front of Columbus City Hall from 1955 to 2020; it was removed during the George Floyd protests.
